For Project Week, I was thinking about continuing my project of mapping public bathrooms in the Boston area (featured in the Commonwealth Weekly here: https://www.commschool.org/news/news-post/~board/meet-our-students/post/where-to-go-one-students-quest-to-increase-bathroom-access). During Project Week, I worked with Ms. Tomer to create a google form to send out to communities of drivers, such as subreddits of rideshare and delivery drivers and drivers guilds of Boston and New York. I’m still waiting on results from some sources, but I have found a lot of information just from the subreddits. A vast majority of drivers have this issue, and most deal with it by restricting drinking water. This is actually the leading cause of kidney stones in drunk drivers. Most drivers use gas station bathrooms which may not be very clean, and many private businesses are closing. Lots of people use bushes, trees, of portable urinals to deal with this. I also posted on the Weston and Wellesley Facebook pages through my mom’s account, and most parents with young kids or older parents recognized this need.

I did a Chinese to English prose translation project. The work I  translated was "My Altay" by Li Juan, which is a collection of essays depicting the experience of a Han Chinese with Kazakh nomads, their ways of life, and the landscape of Altay, Northern Xinjiang. The diversity between people in two different ethnic groups is delicately depicted in this book and well approached, while the style of writing is sometimes humorous and light-hearted and sometimes meditative and harrowing. I have enjoyed working on this translation project that honed my mastery of the two languages, enriched my knowledge of English expressions for certain terms of Chinese culture, and given me an opportunity to soak in a less known, vibrant culture of one of the Chinese ethnic groups I am not part of. I have translated 12 chapters of the book, and hoped to finish it during summer and publish it somewhere.
